  "why": "The fuzzer (KuK) enforces naturalness and semantic-preservation constraints at the per-mutation / per-population level (it initializes populations by adding bounded noise relative to the original seed, forbids affine transforms to keep images 'recognizable by human', and uses an L∞ radius in mutation). However, the paper does not describe a mechanism that enforces semantic consistency or bounds perturbation relative to the original seed across multiple GA iterations (i.e., it constrains per-step changes rather than cumulative distortion across generations). Because KuK controls similarity/perturbation magnitude between successive mutation steps but does not demonstrate explicit control to prevent drift relative to the original seed throughout iterative evolution, the appropriate rating is Medium.",
  "evidence": "Section 4 (Uncommon Data Generation) — Population Initialization (page 746): \"Given an input image, we first generate a set of images by randomly adding noise to it. In order to generate high-quality images (i.e., recognizable by human), we abandon the affine transformation (e.g., translation and rotation [55]) as the crossover may generate invalid images. We use L∞ norm to constrain the allowable changes between the original seed and its generated counterpart.\" (Section 4, Population Initialization)\n\nSection 4 (Crossover and Mutation) (page 746): \"For the crossover, we adopt the tournament selection strategy ... The two selected images are used to perform the crossover by randomly exchanging the corresponding pixels. After the crossover, each image is randomly mutated by adding white noise, to increase the diversity of the population.\" (Crossover and Mutation)\n\nSection 5.1 (RQ3: Usefulness of Test Data Generation) — GA settings (page 746): \"For the mutation process, the radius of L∞ is set as 0.3. For each dataset, we randomly select 200 BEs as the initial seeds. ... The maximum number of the iterations in the genetic algorithm is set to 50.\" (RQ3: Setting)\n\nSection 2.1 (Definitions) — Benign/Adversarial example semantics (page 744): \"Definition 2 (Benign Example). A benign example (BE) x with ground truth label y is an input sample, such that the prediction decision of a DNN M is consistent with the ground truth label: LM(x) = y.\" (Definition 2)\n\nAbsence of cumulative-constraint wording: The GA description constrains per-mutation magnitude (L∞) and initial population relative to the seed, but the paper does not state any mechanism that enforces a global bound on distortion relative to the original seed across iterations nor a human/semantic re-checking step to ensure semantic equivalence is preserved throughout evolution (see Section 4 and Section 5.1 descriptions above)."
